{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509383"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:17:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:17:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11425"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11425"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.02,0.56,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4060"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62491"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4060","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4060"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11425"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47938"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"11061"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5931"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6046"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11180"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19208"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62491"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old nulliparous woman presents to the antenatal clinic at 12 weeks gestation for her booking appointment. During the workup it becomes apparent she has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, for which she takes metformin. Her most recent HbA1c from last month is 7.1%. Her BMI is 41. Her sister had preeclampsia when she was pregnant last year. Her blood pressure is 110/80 mmHg. Urinalysis is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following treatments would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No additional treatment","Methyldopa","Aspirin","Perindopril","Labetalol"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is at risk for developing pre-eclampsia. Some risk factors for pre-eclampsia include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrevious personal/family history of pre-eclampsia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENulliparity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMedical conditions such as autoimmune disease, chronic hypertension, diabetes mellitus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAssisted conception\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand (SOMANZ) have recommend that \u003Cstrong\u003Elow-dose aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E is commenced, ideally before 16 weeks gestation, as prophylaxis for pre-eclampsia in women with risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethyldopa\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Elabetalol\u003C/strong\u003E are both antihypertensive medications approved in pregnancy, however, this patient does not currently have high blood pressure and these medications are not indicated for prophylaxis against pre-eclampsia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerindopril\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in pregnancy. Pregnant women with pre-existing hypertension on an ACE inhibitor medication should be changed to an alternative antihypertensive medication as soon as possible during the first trimester. Use of ACE inhibitors in the second and third trimesters of pregnancy can cause fetal renal dysfunction and oligohydramnios and subsequently fetal death.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low-dose aspirin is recommended as prophylaxis for pre-eclampsia in patients presenting with risk factors","Low-dose aspirin should be initiated prior to 16 weeks after confirmation of viable intrauterine pregnancy"],"references":["Australian Journal of General Practice. Indications for commencing aspirin for the prevention of pregnancy-induced hypertension and pre-eclampsia spectrum disorders [Internet]. Victoria (AU): AJGP; 2022 [cited 2024 March 15]. Available from: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2022/october/indications-for-commencing-aspirin","Podymow T, August P. Antihypertensive drugs in pregnancy. Semin Nephrol. 2011;31(1):70-85.","Antihypertensives - ACE inhibitors - Perindopril. Australian Medicines Handbook 2020 (online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd; 2020 July. Available from: https://amhonline.amh.net.au/ [Accessed 18 April 2022]","Society of Obstetric Medicine of Australia and New Zealand (SOMANZ). Hypertension in Pregnancy Guideline 2023 [Internet]. 2023 [cited 2024 Nov 17]. Available from: https://www.somanz.org/content/uploads/2024/01/SOMANZ_Hypertension_in_Pregnancy_Guideline_2023.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47938"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11425"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47938"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-17T21:16:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-17T21:17:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4060"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62491"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"